</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<h3 id="use-raw-footage">Use Raw Footage</h3>
<p>1 <strong>clear rule</strong>: always record in <strong>raw format</strong> whenever your equipment allows it, because <strong>compressed files</strong> discard subtle pixel and color information that you&#8217;ll need to evaluate anomalies rigorously. You want evidence that&#8217;s reviewable, editable, and resistant to in-camera processing that can mimic phenomena. In <strong>&lt;a class=&quot;wpil_keyword_link&quot; href=&quot;https://cursedtours.com/my-first-night-beginner-<a href="https://cursedtours.com/7-best-derelict-psychiatric-hospital-ghost-stories/">ghost</a>-hunting-gear-secrets/&#8221; title=&#8221;My First Night: Beginner Ghost-Hunting Gear Secrets&#8221; data-wpil-keyword-link=&#8221;linked&#8221; data-wpil-monitor-id=&#8221;9374&#8243;&gt;ghost hunting</a></strong>, raw gives you latitude to adjust exposure, white balance, and shadow detail without introducing artifacts.</p>
<ol>
<li>Preserve sensor data — retain dynamic range for post-analysis.</li>
<li>Maintain timestamp and metadata integrity for chain-of-custody.</li>
<li>Capture multiple codecs if your rig permits, pairing raw with an auxiliary compressed stream.</li>
<li>Archive originals securely and document processing steps to keep authentic footage defensible.</li>
</ol>
<p>Operate methodically, stay skeptical, and protect your freedom to <strong>analyze evidence objectively</strong>.</p>
<h2 id="documenting-witness-testimonies-and-timelines">Documenting Witness Testimonies and Timelines</h2>
<p>Because memory degrades and perception is biased, you should treat <strong>witness statements</strong> as data to be collected systematically rather than as immediate facts. You’ll record identities, timestamps, and environmental conditions, noting changes in witness credibility and cataloging emotional responses separately from factual claims. Use <strong>structured interviews</strong>, closed and calibrated questions, and avoid leading phrasing; transcribe verbatim and mark nonverbal cues. Construct a timeline by aligning <strong>timestamped sensor logs</strong> with witness reports, flagging <strong>inconsistencies</strong> for later corroboration. Quantify certainty levels and annotate hypotheses versus observed reports. Preserve <strong>chain-of-custody metadata</strong> for each testimony file without storing sensitive raw audio insecurely. Maintain audit trails so you can revisit, re-evaluate, and release only what respects <strong>participant consent</strong> and your methodological integrity.</p>
<h2 id="preserving-and-cataloging-raw-evidence-securely">Preserving and Cataloging Raw Evidence Securely</h2>
<p>When you collect <strong>raw evidence</strong>, assume it’ll be needed for later analysis, legal review, or publication, so you should prioritize <strong>unaltered capture</strong>, <strong>verifiable metadata</strong>, and <strong>secure storage</strong> from the moment of acquisition. You’ll label files immediately, record <strong>chain-of-custody notes</strong>, and avoid post-capture edits that could compromise credibility. Use <strong>tamper-evident formats</strong> and redundant backups to maintain integrity.</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Capture</strong>: use write-once media, timestamped files, and embedded metadata.</li>
<li><strong>Catalog</strong>: assign unique IDs, standardized tags, and a searchable index.</li>
<li><strong>Store</strong>: segregate originals in locked physical or encrypted digital vaults; implement evidence storage policies.</li>
<li><strong>Protect</strong>: apply strong data encryption, access controls, and hashed checksums for verification.</li>
</ol>
<p>This approach keeps your files defensible, auditable, and ready for responsible sharing without sacrificing autonomy.</p>
<h2 id="validating-encounters:-analysis-and-peer-review">Validating Encounters: Analysis and Peer Review</h2>
<p>Although you should start with the raw, unaltered files and chain-of-custody records, validating a purported ghost encounter means subjecting every element to structured, reproducible analysis and independent review. You’ll run encounter analysis workflows: timestamp verification, noise-floor assessment, and sensor cross-correlation. You’ll document methods so others can replicate them.</p>
